<DOC><DOCNO> AP881125-0142 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-88 1854EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Libya     11-25 0199</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Italy-Libya,0205</SECOND><HEAD>Libya Says It Will Follow Poison-Weapon Prohibitions</HEAD><DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Libyan official told Italian authorities Friday hiscountry adheres to international rules that prohibit the use ofchemical weapons but not their production, the Foreign Ministry said.   The United States has said Libya is on the verge of producingchemical weapons.   Maj. Abdulsalam Jalloud, considered No. 2 man to Libyan leaderMoammar Gadhafi, was asked about poison gas production during ameeting in Rome with Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti, a ministrystatement said.   Jalloud said Libya adheres to the 1925 Geneva convention, whichbans the use of chemical weapons but not their production andstorage.   In September, the U.S. State Department said it had evidenceLibya was able to make chemical weapons and was on the verge offull-scale production.   Libya has denied the accusation and claimed a new factory,described in reports as a site for chemical weapons manufacture, isa pharmaceutical plant.   Jalloud is the highest-ranking Libyan official to visit Romesince Libya fired a missile at the tiny Sicilian island of Lampedusain April 1986, hours after the U.S. bombing raid on two Libyancoastal cities. Libya is a former Italian colony.</TEXT></DOC>